latestIgtvVideos.title: Book Love: Delhi By Khushwant Singh
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Caution: It's a 7 minutes long but cute book review!

There are lot of ways to fall in love with Delhi. One is this book! I literally felt like traveling time along with the chapters of this book. Although he is being open and blunt about sexual life and body of women but honestly I was completely into the stories and traveling along with the characters. Starting from 1100 AD to the Sikh riots of 1980s this book literally made me travel along and relive Delhi. I always use to fasinate about these places being alive and being in action, and it happened with this book.

From the invaders to Islamic kings, Sufi saints to more invaders, Mugals to British, and Builders to modern brown British ruling India, I think he did justice with all the characters. Looking forward to read more of Khushwant Singh. Just loved it!

#Book #bookstagram #booklover #bookstagrammer #khushwantsingh #bookreview #travel #India #british #stories #blogger #blog #bloggerstyle

latestIgtvVideos.title: Why we don't need Nationalism!
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Ravindra Nath Tagore, first non European to win Nobel Prize in Literature and his visionary words about this whole concept of Nationalism. In less than 08 minutes I tried my best to motivate you read and understand his concept of Nations. You may like it, or maybe not but give it a chance. The books is available online as well. "Never Give In, Never Give Up" that's what it is written on my t-shirt, just if you are wondering. 
The time which we are going through, is making us question a lot and as a common citizen of this planet we have to find and look for the answers now! We cannot avoid these questions anymore. Is it really helping the last poor, last hungry person or last person waiting for justice? Anyways, read it make a call. Thanks @deepikagupta29
for suggesting this one!

#Book #RavindraNathTagore #Nationalism #India #West #Japan

Yes, it is comfortable where you are; yes, it is familiar to what you are doing everyday but ... So, what inspired you to travel for the first time?

latestPosts.caption:
Just another day to celebrate for the sake of it or do we really want to make a change, show a message and implement what is better for nature, humans, society, and other beings of the planet. There is somethings special about cycling, and since childhood this simple machine attracted me towards itself like a magnet. I don’t know what really attracted me to it, the freedom, the democratic nature, the ability to achieve maximum human powered ability, or just simple it is to add so much to our daily lives.

I don’t remember when I saw it for the first time, but I remember a bit of my first tri-cycle which I received as gift in Jaisalmer; I remember the place in my village in Bihar, where I learned how to ride big frame cycles, and I remember how I selected this simple machine again at the age of 25 when I was in Mysore. There is something special about cycles, how humans can balance it on two wheels, how they suddenly make the person who is riding it calm, and how the whole area is free of ego and sound of engines. Once upon a time they use to be proud of Indian roads, from villages to cities, cycles were part of households and to have one use to be matter of prestige. Indian became one of the biggest manufacturer of cycles in the world; but we stopped on a few steps! Right when we were supposed to take it to next level, we decided to bow down to car and fuel lobby. Instead of making our cities cycle and people friendly, we decided to copy the great useless American car model and since then failing every single day on the streets of India. More honking, more air pollution, more anger, more traffic, more waste of fuel, and more accidents. Well, we still have time and cycles can change it.

There are several case studies, that how this machine is liberal, feminist, democratic and support equal rights. From increasing the number of female students in Bihar government schools, when they received cycles to this becoming a global case study; we can still turn the wave and make India cycle friendly. I truly believe in this! The Dutch invest approx. 595 million euros in cycling infrastructure and save approx. 19 billion euros on health bills /- continued in comments ...

latestPosts.caption:
Paris, शहर के निवासी अपने शहर को पेरी बुलाते है, बचपन से कुछ ज्यादा ही सुना था इस शहर के बारे में। कभी लन्दन, न्यूयॉर्क, जाने की इच्छा नहीं हुई, लेकिन पेरिस जाने की जरूर थी, बचपन से। प्यारा शहर है, शांत लोग है, पर्यटकों की भीड़ से दूर कुछ बहुत ही खूबसूरत गलियों में अलग अलग तहर के आर्टिस्ट रहते है, आप सड़क पे चलते हुए उनकी खिड़की से देख सकते है; कोई पेंटिंग कर रहा है, कोई कविता लिख रहा है और कोई बिजी है, हाथ से मूर्ति गढ़ने में। हालांकि किसी के खिड़की से अंदर देखना नहीं चाहिए, लेकिन मुझे लगता है कि इन लोगों ने जाने में ऐसा किया है, की लोग देखे, आर्ट और आर्टिस्ट दोनों को और वैसे भी इस शहर के लोगों को कुछ भी छुपा कर करना पसंद नहीं है। किस करते हुए आपको युवा और उम्रदराज लोग दोनों दिख जाएंगे, प्यार दिखाने और जताने में लोग हिचकते नहीं है। शहर जिंदा है, यहां के लोग भी जिंदा है, हालांकि फैशन और कैपिटलिज्म के दौर में कुछ लोग बहुत थके हुए भी नजर आए, जैसे उनको पेरिस बिल्कुल नहीं भा रहा है, लेकिन रहना पड़ रहा है। सड़क के किनारे अनगिनत कैफे और रेस्टोरेंट, शांत माहौल, कोई गाड़ी हॉर्न बजा कर अपने बाप का पैसा दिखाने की कोशिश नहीं कर रही थी, किसी भी गाड़ी के पीछे उनका जात या धर्म भी नहीं चिपका था। 

माहौल ऐसा की आप दोस्तो और प्रियजनों के साथ बाहर बैठ कर एक अच्छी वाइन या बीयर पी सकते है, अनेक नॉन एल्कोहोलिक ड्रिंक्स भी है, पर अच्छे सूरज के साथ, एक बीयर तो बनती है। यहां के लोग दारू छुपा कर नहीं पीते, शायद हम भारतीयों को काफी कुछ छुपा कर करने की आदत हो गई है, वैसे तो ये बहुत ही बेहूदा आदत है, पर आदत एक दिन और जनरेशन में नहीं जाती है। सुना है, पेरिस ने भी बहुत कुछ झेला है, दर्द सहे है और अगर आज ये विश्व का सबके ज्यादा बड़ा पर्यटन नगर है और उसके पीछे मेहनत है, यहां के लोगों की, जो जिंदा है, अपना हक जानते है। जानते है कि साफ पानी, साफ हवा, सड़क के चलने के लिए शांत माहौल, साइकिल चलाने के लिए एक पूरी लेन, कोई गंदगी न फैलाते हुए लोकल और टूरिस्ट, समय पे चलते हुए बस और मेट्रो, और अपना हक हुक्मरानों के लेना, यहां के लोगों से सीखने लोग्य है। 

खैर, पेरिस को ज्यादा रोमांटसाइज नहीं करूंगा, हर शहर में कमियां होती है, यह भी है। पर कभी खुद आइए और एक्सपीरियंस कीजिए। क्योंकि शमी कपूर का एक गाना था, ऐसा मौका फिर कहा मिलेगा, देखो देखो, ऐन इवनिंग इन पेरिस।

latestPosts.caption:
Cycling Capital, Amsterdam. One thing which keeps me in awe in this region of the world is, their relationship with cycles. You can ride your cycles without any fear of someone hitting you or honking at you. In fact, cars will drive behind calmly until they get their way, they know that people who are walking and cycling have more rights than cars. Cycling makes these cities liveable for humans, a sense of calmness prevails in the city. 

Cars also have better infrastructure and drivers have more common sense! Here it is not about the bigger, the better. It is all about what is needed. Their e-car charging facility is much better than all hyped India. People know how to drive, and how to park !! Cycle and walking paths are never obstructed. And our mentality is like, 'पैदल ही तो चल रहा है, साइड से निकाल जाएगा।'

It is not that cities like Amsterdam were always like this. A few hundred deaths because of road accidents and especially kids, changed everything. They decided to move back to cycles. In India we are heartless, more than 400 people die everyday in road accidents; we really don't care about human lives. Even small cities and villages in India, are not doing anything about cycling. They say that, yes Amsterdam or Copenhagen can do it because they are not as hot as us; but they are brutally cold, and we can still ride for 7-8 months a year easily.

Once I wrote a letter to Delhi Metro to make a cycle parking at Preet Vihar metro station, they replied they don't have space. Seriously for cycle parking? So, it is not really the intention to make something happen but attitude which is so casual and wanna be so much is status quo, that any change seems impossible.

Anyways, cannot just rant about something not happening, but make it happen. At our organisation along with Delhi By Cycle we are starting a non profit, Public Mobility Project @publicmobilityproject and to start working on advocacy to make India more cycle friendly, one city, one town and one village at a time. If you also understand the value of making cities more cycle and walking friendly, maybe you want to fill up this google form, link in bio of PMP.

Fabindia in collaboration with Delhi by Cycle was an enriching experience!

Our journey kicked off at DBC meeting point, surrounded by stunning graffiti that showcased the city’s rich cultural tapestry. The route took us through the picturesque Lodhi Art District, past iconic heritage sites, and along scenic city streets.

Decked out in Fabindia’s comfortable trousers, in various styles and fits, our DBC riders enjoyed a relaxed and effortless ride. The comfort fit and drawstring waistband provided a full range of motion, making pedaling and manoeuvring through city streets a breeze.

It was all smiles as we wrapped up our ride at Fabindia’s Khan Market store. A huge thank you to DBC for co-creating this unforgettable experience and we look forward to more such adventures!

latestPosts.caption:
So, just sharing some pictures from the beautiful 8 day workshop in Dharwar, Karnataka. Where life was all about:

- Questioning, beyond conditions & what we think we already know
- Slow living, healthy food, barefoot walks, waking up with birds, and being grounded
- Doing a lot of hand work, which finally reached making a tree house (helping an expert) on the last day
- Meeting inspiring people, who are living an alternative life in the world where it is not allowed so
- Living in a forest farm, which was a barren land 25 years ago
- Looking at life from a complete difference perspective 
- A lot of chai & chai
- Late night star gazing and talking about aliens
- Music, poetry, art, learnings, and self-less giving
- Finding some amazing friends, new members to tribe
- Living under a banyan tree and realising that we don't need a lot in life

And much more, maybe you want to go and spend some time in this beautiful workshop in a forest farm or you just want to read in depth, how was it for me. Well, head to the blog (link in bio).

At the end it was not about what I gained but more about how I felt. So, maybe you also want to go there but not just because you are looking for something but also because you want to look at things differently.
